<p>DuckDuckGo is a search engine. Like Google Search, you just throw some keywords into a box and get a list of results. Lots of people use Google, but I don&rsquo;t. DuckDuckGo works better for me, and this is why.</p>
<figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://lambdaland.org/content/images/2019/01/DuckDuckGo-Logo--Horizontal@3x.png" class="kg-image"><figcaption>The Duck</figcaption></figure>
## Consistent Results
<p>Did you know that Google will give you different search results, based on who you are and what you have searched for in the past? This is called a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Filter_bubble">filter bubble</a>, and it&rsquo;s <a href="https://spreadprivacy.com/google-filter-bubble-study/">annoying and dangerous</a>. DuckDuckGo doesn&rsquo;t put you in a filter bubble.</p>
<h2 id="goodies-and-tools">
  Goodies and Tools
  <a class="anchor" href="#goodies-and-tools">#</a>
</h2>
<p>Oh, man do I love the tools DuckDuckGo gives software developers. Here are just a few.</p>
<h4 id="software-development">
  Software Development
  <a class="anchor" href="#software-development">#</a>
</h4>
<ul>
<li>Need to find a color? Search &ldquo;color picker&rdquo;. A built-in color picker pops up.</li>
<li>Want to know the HTML character entity for, say, the interrobang? (â€½) Type &ldquo;HTML entity â€½&rdquo;</li>
<li>Got some JSON that you need to prettify? Search &ldquo;json validator&rdquo; for a validator and beautifier.</li>
<li>Searching Stack Overflow, Mozilla Developer Network, etc. with Bangs! (more later)</li>
<li>Keybinding references for Emacs, Vim, Bash, etc.</li>
</ul>
<figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://lambdaland.org/content/images/2019/01/Screen-Shot-2019-01-14-at-22.07.42-1.png" class="kg-image"><figcaption>Emacs cheat sheet (expands to show more keystrokes)</figcaption></figure>
#### Entertainment
<ul>
<li>Need to play 2048? Yes, just search &ldquo;2048&rdquo; and an in-browser game pops up.</li>
<li>Today&rsquo;s XKCD (search &ldquo;xkcd&rdquo;)</li>
<li>Cheat sheets for Kerbal Space Program, Minecraft, League of Legends, etc.</li>
</ul>
<h4 id="bangs">
  Bangs
  <a class="anchor" href="#bangs">#</a>
</h4>
<p>Perform special operations by putting the appropriate !-sequence at the beginning of your search.</p>
<ul>
<li><code>!yt</code> Search YouTube (&quot;!yt glitter bomb package&quot;)</li>
<li><code>!a</code> Search Amazon</li>
<li><code>!w</code> Search Wikipedia</li>
<li><code>!mdn</code> Search Mozilla Developer Network</li>
<li><code>!unsplash</code> Search Unsplash photos</li>
<li><code>!img</code> Search Google imagesâ€”proxied for you so you can keep your privacy</li>
<li><code>!ldss</code> Search LDS Scriptures (just found this one ðŸ¤¯</li>
</ul>
<p>There are thousands. Literally.</p>
<h4 id="misc">
  Misc.
  <a class="anchor" href="#misc">#</a>
</h4>
<ul>
<li>Generate Lorem Ipsum filler text by searching &ldquo;lorem ipsum&rdquo;</li>
<li>Check the weather with &ldquo;weather <code>&lt;zipcode&gt;/&lt;city name&gt;</code>&rdquo;</li>
<li>Calculator with &ldquo;calculator&rdquo;</li>
</ul>
<figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://lambdaland.org/content/images/2019/01/Screen-Shot-2019-01-14-at-21.53.19-1.png" class="kg-image"><figcaption>Searching the weather</figcaption></figure>
<p>For a full list of instant answers, see <a href="https://duck.co/ia">here</a>.</p>
<p>For a full list of Bang-directives, see <a href="https://duckduckgo.com/bang">here</a>.</p>
<p>It&rsquo;s incredible. It&rsquo;s simple. Perhaps best of all, ad-free! Well, they do display ads based on your search term for <em>just that search</em>. They don&rsquo;t track you. The ads are not customized to <em>you</em>, rather they are customized to your <em>search</em>. They&rsquo;re not intrusive either. I forgot they were there until I was typing this. ðŸ˜„</p>
<p>But seriously. DuckDuckGo is amazing. Give it a try.</p>
<p>You can even enable it as your default search engine on iOS. Go to Settings &gt; Safari &gt; Search Engine and select DuckDuckGo. You can set it as well in Safari on desktop, as well as Firefox. (I don&rsquo;t use Chrome or Edge, though I imagine they&rsquo;d let you do the same. Comment below if you find anything out.</p>
